Introduction

Dataset Description¶

This dataset contains 100k medical appointments iinformation from Brazil. Its purpose is to know why do patients not show up to their appointements. To help us know why we have :

  • 100k rows containing appointement information.
  • columns (or variables). Here is the columns list of names and what they represent

'AppointmentID' : Identification of each appointment
'Gender' : M or F representing respectively Male or Female
'ScheduledDay' : It indicates when did the patient book an appointment
'AppointmentDay' : When is the appointment taking place
'Age' : How old is the patient
'Neighbourhood' : Where is the appointment located
'Scholarship' : Does the patient have medical financial aid or not
'Hipertension' : Is the patient suffering from hypertension ? yes or no represented by 1 or 0
'Diabetes' : Is the patient suffering from diabetes ? yes or no represented by 1 or 0
'Alcoholism' : Is the patient suffering from alcoholism ? yes or no represented by 1 or 0
'Handcap' : Is the patient handicaped ? yes or no represented by 1 or 0
'SMS_received' : Did the patient receive an SMS ? yes or no represented by 1 or 0
'No-show' : Did the patient not show up? yes for he didn't show up or no for he did show up

Questions to be answered

1. Is the abscence higher in a gender more than another?

2. Is the abscence higher in older age than younger ones?

3. Is showing up higher in a specific period/date/month more than another?

Is showing up higher when schedule date and appointment date are the same?

4. Is the abscence higher for specific neighbours more than others?

5. Do people having scholarship attend more to their consultation because it is free

6. Does the abscence dependent on the type of the disease is it an emergency or not : (Hipertension, Diabetes , Alcoholism, Handcap)

7. Do people receiving SMS tned to show up more than others?

In [40]:
def pie_chart(title,expression_to_plot):
    plt.pie(expression_to_plot, labels = ['show-up', 'no show-up'], colors=['palegreen', 'lightgrey'], 
    startangle=270, shadow = True, explode = (0, 0.1),
    radius = 1.0, autopct = '%1.1f%%')
    # plot title
    plt.title(title, fontweight="bold")
    # showing the plot
    plt.show()

Before plotting the graph I would like to define a function for ploting so that I will have the same theme all over the notebook and without re-writing the ploting code each time¶

In [51]:
def plot_sidebyside(col_name,top_y_lim, axis_label="Number of Patients"):
    global df
    g = sns.catplot(x="no_show", col=col_name, col_wrap=5,
                data= df,
                kind="count", height=3, aspect=.8,sharey=True, palette =sns.color_palette(['palegreen', 'lightgrey']))
    #setting axis label and xtick labels
    (g.set_axis_labels("", axis_label)
      .set_xticklabels(['Did show up', 'Did not show up']))
    #precising the bottom and the limit to have unifor plotting across many graphs
    plt.ylim(0, top_y_lim)
    return plt.show();

In [62]:
#I will make some modifications to the columns of the diseases replacing the 1 with the name of the disease
#to not repeat the same code I have create a function to edit the columns easily
def replace_col(disease,from_value=1,to_value='optional'):
    global df
    if to_value == 'optional':
        df[disease].replace({from_value:disease}, inplace=True)
        return df[disease]
    else :
        df[disease].replace({from_value:to_value}, inplace=True)
        return df[disease]
#I made the if statement because I wasn't able to write: def replace_col(disease,from_value=1,to_value=disease):
#so I used this method

From the General Visualization we can conclude that :
1)
month_appoin and month_sched has the highest values of patients for the 5th month </li>
the most important number of patient are aged between 0 and 70 approximately</li>
most patient don't have scholarships</li>
From all the disease handicaped are the smallest proportion of patients</li>
From all the disease the not sick patients are the bigger in numbers than the sick patients</li>
2)
The number of patients showing up to their appointement is higher</li>
3)
The number of females equals approximately twice the number of males</li>

After answering question 1

(Is the absence higher in one gender more than another? )

We conclude that there is no specific gender that misses the appointement more than the other

After answering question 2

( Is the absence higher in older age than younger ones? ) We can conclude that young people tend to show up less than old people

---> showing up is higher among old patients as compared to young patients' show up rate

</br>

After answering question 3

(Is showing up higher in a specific month more than another? )


We can conclude that the regardeless of the appointement month the abscence or presence rate to an appointement is constant


After answering Additional question

( Is showing up higher when schedule date and appointment date are the same? )

-->We can conclude that when the appointement date is the same as the scheduling date patient tend to show up more as compared to patients who have their appointement date different from the shceduling date


Is it that people forget about their appointement if it is not in the same date?

we can not know through this data alone we need further investigation and more data

After answering question 4

(Is the absence higher for specific neighborhoods than others? )
(limitation) We can further investigate what can be the causes of this lower percentages of showing-up but

Seeing how the vast majority of neighborhoods having approximetly the same percentages of presence and abscence

We can conclude that people tend to show up or not to their appointement independently of the neighberhood

After answering question 5

(Do people having scholarship attend more to their consultation because it is free )
(limitation) we can not conclude that having no scholarship makes the patient wants to attend more. Instead

-->We can conclude that having a scholarship does not influence the show up rate to become higher

After answering question 6

(Does the absence dependent on the type of the disease is it an emergency or not : (Hipertension, Diabetes , Alcoholism, Handcap) )
Percentages of not suffering or suffering from a specific disease by the show up rate are approximately the same

We can conclude that showing up does not depend of a specific disease more than another

We can conclude that showing up does not depend of suffering or not from a specific disease

After answering question 7

(Do people receiving SMS tend to show up more than others? )
It is quite clear that even though patients received an SMS reminder but their show up rate (72.4%) is less than the show up rate of patients who did not receive an sms (83.3%) (limitation)

-->But we can not concluding that showing up does depend of suffering not sending a message we need more information to understand this relationship
